{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608151"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:30:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:30:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15987"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15987"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.72,0.04,0.24,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8678"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73461"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8678","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8678"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15987"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58930"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8605"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20770"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20773"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73461"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryonic development, three primary germ layers form in the third week after fertilisation. Each germ layer - ectoderm, mesoderm, and endoderm - gives rise to specific tissues and organs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures develops from the ectoderm?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Central nervous system and epidermis","Gastrointestinal tract epithelium","Connective tissue of skin","Blood vessels and heart muscle","Vertebrae and ribs"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ectoderm gives rise to the \u003Cstrong\u003Ecentral nervous system and epidermis\u003C/strong\u003E, including the brain, spinal cord, peripheral nerves, and skin appendages like sweat glands and hair follicles. Neural crest cells, also derived from ectoderm, form melanocytes and parts of the face and neck.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options arise from other germ layers:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Egastrointestinal tract epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E develops from endoderm, along with the liver, pancreas, and respiratory tract lining\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Econnective tissue of skin\u003C/strong\u003E (dermis) develops from mesoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eblood vessels and heart muscle\u003C/strong\u003E develop from mesoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evertebrae and ribs\u003C/strong\u003E develop from mesoderm (specifically somites)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding germ layer derivatives is crucial for comprehending both normal development and congenital abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ectoderm forms neural tissue, neural crest derivatives, epidermis, and associated structures like sweat glands and hair follicles.","Neural crest cells from ectoderm form melanocytes, peripheral nerves, and parts of the face and neck.","Endoderm forms the gastrointestinal tract and associated organs, while mesoderm forms connective tissues and circulatory system."],"references":["Ansari A, Pillarisetty LS. Embryology, Ectoderm. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539836/","Gaillard R, Steegers EA, de Jongste JC, Hofman A, Jaddoe VW. Tracking of fetal growth characteristics during different trimesters and the risks of adverse birth outcomes. Int J Epidemiol. 2014 Aug;43(4):1140-53. doi: 10.1093/ije/dyu036. Epub 2014 Mar 5. PMID: 24603318; PMCID: PMC4258770","Chen X, Liu H, Li Y, Zhang W, Zhou A, Xia W, Xu S. First-trimester fetal size, accelerated growth in utero, and child neurodevelopment in a cohort study. BMC Med. 2024 Apr 29;22(1):181. doi: 10.1186/s12916-024-03390-3. PMID: 38685041; PMCID: PMC11059611","Godfrey KM, Inskip HM, Hanson MA. The long-term effects of prenatal development on growth and metabolism. Semin Reprod Med. 2011 May;29(3):257-65. doi: 10.1055/s-0031-1275518. Epub 2011 Jul 18. PMID: 21769765; PMCID: PMC3685133","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58930"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15987"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58930"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T21:15:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T21:16:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8678"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73461"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt"